Den I. E. Davies 1929 Prehistoric & Roman Remains of Denbighshire, 216-8. Fig. 64 shows front face (photo). Found when cutting deep trench or drain, c. 2½ ft. under the surface. "It lay in a stratum of clay boggy ground. It appears to have been fixed of discovery). Davies says that this celt 'shows unmistakable signs of having been hafted, there being around the middle a band of brown stained surface.' (p. 218). This appears to show clearly on Davies' photo, but there's nothing totally convincing on the object itself. Most of the band seems to be differentially stained 'impurities' in flint, but there are suggestions of a clearer band on the photo celt than it now has: a b+w photo of it now would make comparison easier.
